'''Asparagus''', or '''garden asparagus''', folk name '''sparrow grass''',  scientific name '''''Asparagus officinalis''''', is a [[perennial]] [[flowering plant]] species in the genus ''[[Asparagus (genus)|Asparagus]]''. Its young shoots are used as a spring [[vegetable]]. 

It was once classified in the [[lily]] family, like the related ''[[Allium]]'' species, [[onion]]s and [[garlic]]. However, genetic research places lilies, ''Allium'', and asparagus in three separate families&amp;mdash;the [[Liliaceae]], [[Amaryllidaceae]], and [[Asparagaceae]], respectively&amp;mdash;with the Amaryllidaceae and Asparagaceae being grouped together in the order [[Asparagales]]. Sources differ as to the native range of ''Asparagus officinalis'', but generally include most of Europe and western [[temperate Asia]].&lt;ref name=&quot;POWO_531229-1&quot;&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.plantsoftheworldonline.org/taxon/urn:lsid:ipni.org:names:531229-1|title=Asparagus officinalis L.|last=Plants of the World Online.|date=n.d.|publisher=Royal Botanic Gardens, Kew|accessdate=31 May 2018}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;fe&quot;&gt;{{cite web|url=http://rbg-web2.rbge.org.uk/cgi-bin/nph-readbtree.pl/feout?FAMILY_XREF=&amp;GENUS_XREF=Asparagus&amp;SPECIES_XREF=officinalis&amp;TAXON_NAME_XREF=&amp;RANK=|title=Asparagus officinalis|last=Flora Europaea.|date=n.d.|publisher=Royal Botanic Garden Edinburgh|accessdate=19 May 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=&quot;empp&quot;&gt;{{cite web|url=http://ww2.bgbm.org/_EuroPlusMed/PTaxonDetail.asp?NameId=38660&amp;PTRefFk=500000|title=Asparagus officinalis|last=Euro+Med Plantbase Project.|date=|publisher=Botanic Garden and Botanical Museum Berlin-Dahlem|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110811083221/http://ww2.bgbm.org/_EuroPlusMed/PTaxonDetail.asp?NameId=38660&amp;PTRefFk=500000|archivedate=11 August 2011|accessdate=19 May 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=grin&gt;{{GRIN | accessdate=19 May 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt; It is widely cultivated as a vegetable crop.

== Biology ==
[[File:Asparagus Tip.jpg|thumb|upright|Asparagus shoot before becoming woody]]

Asparagus is a [[herbaceous]], [[perennial plant]]&lt;ref name=&quot;prota&quot;&gt;{{cite book|title=Plant Resources of Tropical Africa 2: Vegetables|last=|first=|publisher=PROTA Foundation, Wageningen; Backhuys, Leiden; CTA, Wageningen|year=2004|isbn=|editor1-last=Grubben|editor1-first=G.J.H.|location=|pages=|editor2-last=Denton|editor2-first=O.A.}}&lt;/ref&gt; growing to {{convert|100|–|150|cm|in|sigfig=1|abbr=on}} tall, with stout stems with much-branched, feathery foliage. The &quot;leaves&quot; are in fact needle-like cladodes ([[Aerial stem modification|modified stems]]) in the axils of scale leaves; they are {{convert|6|–|32|mm|in|frac=32|abbr=on}} long and {{convert|1|mm|in|frac=32|abbr=on}} broad, and clustered four to 15 together, in a rose-like shape.&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite book|title=The Encyclopedia of Diderot &amp; d'Alembert|last=Diderot|first=D.|date=2009|publisher=|isbn=|location=|pages=|chapter=Asparagus|accessdate=1 April 2015|orig-year=1772|chapter-url=http://quod.lib.umich.edu/cgi/t/text/text-idx?c=did;cc=did;rgn=main;view=text;idno=did2222.0001.298|via=Collaborative Translation Project, University of Michigan}}&lt;/ref&gt; The root system, often referred to as a &quot;crown,&quot; is [[Adventitiousness#Roots|adventitious]] and the root type is [[Fascicle (botany)|fasciculated]].  The [[flower]]s are bell-shaped, greenish-white to yellowish, {{convert|4.5|–|6.5|mm|in|frac=32|abbr=on}} long, with six [[tepal]]s partially fused together at the base; they are produced singly or in clusters of two or three in the junctions of the branchlets. It is usually [[plant sexuality|dioecious]], with male and female flowers on separate plants, but sometimes hermaphrodite flowers are found. The [[fruit]] is a small red [[Berry (botany)|berry]] {{convert|6-10|mm|in|frac=32|abbr=on}} in diameter, which is [[toxin|toxic]] to humans.&lt;ref name=&quot;gardengrow.co.nz&quot;&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.gardengrow.co.nz/plant/Asparagus|title=Growing Asparagus|last=Garden Grow.|date=n.d.|access-date=19 November 2019}}&lt;/ref&gt;

Plants native to the western coasts of [[Europe]] (from northern [[Spain]] to northwest [[Germany]], north [[Ireland]], and [[Great Britain]]) are treated as ''Asparagus officinalis'' subsp. ''prostratus'' {{small|(Dumort.) Corb.}}, distinguished by its low-growing, often prostrate stems growing to only {{convert|30|–|70|cm|in|abbr=on}} high, and shorter cladodes {{convert|2|–|18|mm|in|frac=32|abbr=on}} long.&lt;ref name=&quot;fe&quot; /&gt;&lt;ref name=blamey /&gt; It is treated as a distinct species, ''Asparagus prostratus'' {{small|Dumort}}, by some authors.&lt;ref name=&quot;fnwe&quot;&gt;{{cite web|url=http://ip30.eti.uva.nl/BIS/flora.php?selected=beschrijving&amp;menuentry=soorten&amp;id=4839|title=Asparagus prostratus (Asparagus, Wild)|last1=Stace|first1=C.|authorlink=Clive Stace|editor-last=van der Meijden|editor-first=R. |date=|work=Interactive Flora of NW Europe|publisher=ETI BioInformatics|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090923070246/http://ip30.eti.uva.nl/BIS/flora.php?selected=beschrijving&amp;menuentry=soorten&amp;id=4839|archive-date=23 September 2009|access-date=19 May 2010|editor2-last=de Kort|editor2-first=I. }}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=grin1&gt;
{{GRIN | ''Asparagus prostratus'' | 5538 | accessdate = 19 May 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt;

== History ==
Asparagus has been used as a vegetable owing to its distinct flavor, and in medicine due to its [[diuretic]] properties and its purported function as an [[aphrodisiac]]. It is pictured as an offering on an Egyptian [[frieze]] dating to 3000 BC. In ancient times, it was also known in Syria and in Spain. Greeks and Romans ate it fresh when in season, and dried the vegetable for use in winter. Roman [[Epicureanism|Epicureans]] froze its sprouts high in the Alps for the Feast of [[Epicurus]]. Emperor [[Augustus]] created the &quot;Asparagus Fleet&quot; for hauling the vegetable, and coined the expression &quot;faster than cooking asparagus&quot; for quick action.&lt;ref group=&quot;Note&quot; name=August&gt;Latin ''velocius quam asparagi conquantur'' (or ''celerius quam asparagi cocuntur''), ascribed to Augustus by [[Suetonius]] (''The Lives of the Twelve Caesars, Book 2 ''(Augustus), para. 87). See [[List of Latin phrases (V)]].&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=Brunning&gt;{{cite journal
 |url=http://www.iwfs.org/assets/upload/regions/europe-africa/Food_and_Wine/Food__Wine_June_2010_1.pdf
 |title=Asparagus – Liliaceae–Asparagacease
 |author=Brunning, Pam
 |journal=Food &amp; Wine
 |date=June 2010
 |issue=103
 |accessdate=26 August 2011
 }}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=SAA_1&gt;{{cite web
 |url=http://www.asperge.nl/nl/overasperge/oudheid/
 |title=Over asperge – Oudheid
 |language=Dutch
 |publisher=Stichting Afzetbevordering Asperges
 |accessdate=26 August 2011
 }}&lt;/ref&gt;

A recipe for cooking asparagus is given in one of the oldest surviving collections of recipes ([[Apicius]]'s third-century BC ''[[De re coquinaria]]'', Book III). In the second century AD, the Greek physician [[Galen]], highly respected within Roman society, mentioned asparagus as a beneficial herb, but as dominance of the Roman empire waned, asparagus' medicinal value drew little attention&lt;ref name=&quot;OBFP&quot;&gt;{{cite book
 |last1=Vaughan
 |first1=John Griffith
 |last2=Geissler
 |first2=Catherine Alison
 |last3=Nicholson
 |first3=Barbara
 |title=The New Oxford Book of Food Plants
 |url=https://archive.org/details/newoxfordbookoff00vaug_0
 |url-access=registration
 |publisher=Oxford University Press
 |year=1997
 }}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref group=&quot;Note&quot; name=anno1000&gt;
In the eleventh century AD the word &quot;sparagus&quot; appeared in an English text. See Brunning (June 2010), p. 6.&amp;nbsp;– Brunning uses the term &quot;in print&quot;, though no printing technique was used in England at the time. In the same sentence, she states that ''peasants'' often called it &quot;sparrow grass&quot;, and further on mentions a 1667 diary in which Samuel Pepys bought a bundle of &quot;sparrow grass&quot; in Fenchurch Street, London.&lt;/ref&gt;
until [[:s:Author:Muhammad al-Nafzawi|al-Nafzawi]]'s ''[[The Perfumed Garden]]''. That piece of writing celebrates its purported [[aphrodisiac]]al &lt;!--adj: http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/aphrodisiac--&gt; power that the Indian ''[[Ananga Ranga]]'' attributes to &quot;special [[phosphorus]] elements&quot; that also counteract fatigue.{{Dubious |reason=The Ananga Ranga was written a century or two before phosphorus was isolated, so it's unlikely to have attributed anything to phosphorus. If anyone can find phosphorus in the Ananga Ranga, please cite the place. |date=May 2020}} 

By 1469, asparagus was cultivated in French monasteries. Asparagus appears to have been little noticed in England until 1538,&lt;ref group=&quot;Note&quot; name=anno1000 /&gt; and in Germany until 1542.&lt;ref name=SAA_1 /&gt;

The ''points d'amour'' (&quot;love tips&quot;) were served as a delicacy to [[Madame de Pompadour]].&lt;ref name=witgoud_1&gt;{{cite web
 |url          = http://eten-en-drinken.infoyo.nl/producten/14450-wit-goud-en-koningin-der-groente-vorstelijke-asperges.html
 |title        = Wit goud en koningin der groente: vorstelijke asperges
 |language     = Dutch
 |publisher    = Infoyo (web publisher)
 |location     = Netherlands
 |date         = 20 May 2009
 |accessdate   = 26 August 2011
 |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20120119040848/http://eten-en-drinken.infoyo.nl/producten/14450-wit-goud-en-koningin-der-groente-vorstelijke-asperges.html
 |archive-date = 19 January 2012
 |url-status     = dead
 |df           = dmy-all
}}&lt;/ref&gt;

Asparagus was brought to North America by European settlers at least as early as 1655. Adriaen van der Donck, a Dutch immigrant to New Netherland, mentions asparagus in his description of Dutch farming practices in the New World.&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite book|last1=Blackburn|first1=Roderic H.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nK5Au-cvOTwC|title=New World Dutch Studies: Dutch Arts and Culture in Colonial America, 1609-1776 : Proceedings of the Symposium|last2=Kelley|first2=Nancy A.|publisher=SUNY Press|isbn=978-1-4384-2989-2|language=en}}&lt;/ref&gt; Asparagus was grown by British immigrants as well; in 1685, one of William Penn's advertisements for Pennsylvania included asparagus in a long list of crops that grew well in the American climate.&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite book|last=Murphy|first=Andrew R.|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GTpxDwAAQBAJ|title=William Penn: A Life|date=8 October 2018|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-023426-3|language=en}}&lt;/ref&gt;

== Uses ==
Only young asparagus shoots are commonly eaten: once the buds start to open (&quot;ferning out&quot;), the shoots quickly turn woody.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web |url=http://www.hort.purdue.edu/hort/ext/pubs/ho/ho_096.pdf |title=Growing Asparagus in the Home Garden; Section on harvesting |page=2 |publisher=Purdue University Cooperative Extension Service |accessdate=31 January 2014}}&lt;/ref&gt;

Water makes up 93% of asparagus's composition.&lt;ref&gt;Snyder, Harry. (1908). &quot;Human Foods and their Nutritive value&quot;. The MacMillan Company.&lt;/ref&gt; Asparagus is low in [[food energy]] and very low in sodium. It is a good source of [[vitamin B6|vitamin B&lt;sub&gt;6&lt;/sub&gt;]], calcium, magnesium, and zinc, and a very good source of [[dietary fibre]], protein, beta-carotene, vitamin C, vitamin E, vitamin K, thiamin, riboflavin, [[rutin]], [[niacin]], [[folic acid]], iron, phosphorus, [[potassium]], copper, manganese, and selenium,&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://nutritiondata.self.com/facts/vegetables-and-vegetable-products/2311/2|title=Nutrition Facts}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.ars.usda.gov/SP2UserFiles/Place/12354500/Data/SR23/reports/sr23fg11.pdf USDA Agricultural Research Service Data section 11 (pg 61)] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120113064505/http://www.ars.usda.gov/SP2UserFiles/Place/12354500/Data/SR23/reports/sr23fg11.pdf |date=13 January 2012 }}&lt;/ref&gt; as well as [[chromium]], a trace mineral that regulates the ability of insulin to transport glucose from the bloodstream into cells.&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite journal|last=Anderson|first=R A|date=October 1997|title=Nutritional factors influencing the glucose/insulin system: chromium.|journal=Journal of the American College of Nutrition|volume=16|issue=5|pages=404–410|doi=10.1080/07315724.1997.10718705|pmid=9322187|issn=0731-5724}}&lt;/ref&gt; The [[amino acid]] [[asparagine]] gets its name from asparagus, as the asparagus plant is relatively rich in this compound.

The shoots are prepared and served in a number of ways around the world, typically as an appetizer&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=https://theforkedspoon.com/roasted-asparagus-recipe/|title=The Forked Spoon|last=Randhawa|first=Jessica|date=1 July 2019|website=The Forked spoon|access-date=29 November 2019}}&lt;/ref&gt; or vegetable side dish. In Asian-style cooking, asparagus is often [[stir-fried]].  [[Cantonese cuisine|Cantonese]] restaurants in the United States often serve asparagus stir-fried with [[chicken]], [[shrimp]], or [[beef]]. It may also be quickly grilled over charcoal or hardwood embers, and is also used as an ingredient in some stews and soups. In recent years,{{when|date=August 2017}} asparagus eaten raw, as a component of a salad, has regained popularity.&lt;ref&gt;[http://123recipes.com/Recipe/A-To-Z-Salad/Detail Salad Recipe] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100719041545/http://123recipes.com/Recipe/A-To-Z-Salad/Detail |date=19 July 2010 }}&lt;/ref&gt;

Asparagus can also be [[pickled]] and stored for several years. Some brands label shoots prepared in this way as &quot;marinated&quot;.

Stem thickness indicates the age of the plant (and not the age of the stalk), with the thicker stems coming from older plants. Older, thicker stalks can be woody, although peeling the skin at the base removes the tough layer. Peeled asparagus will poach much faster.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web
 |url=http://www.drgourmet.com/ingredients/asparagus.shtml|title=Ingredients – Asparagus
 |publisher=DrGourmet.com
 |accessdate=20 July 2011
 }}&lt;/ref&gt; The bottom portion of asparagus often contains sand and soil, so thorough cleaning is generally advised before cooking.  Plants bearing seeds produce spears that are smaller and thinner, and plants without seeds produce larger and thicker spears.&lt;ref name=&quot;UIllinoisExtension&quot;&gt;{{cite web |last1=Wolford |first1=Ron |last2=Banks |first2=Drusilla |title=Asparagus |url=https://web.extension.illinois.edu/veggies/asparagus.cfm |website=Watch Your Garden Grow |publisher=University of Illinois Extension |accessdate=May 3, 2020}}&lt;/ref&gt;  Thickness and thinness are not an indication of tenderness or toughness.  The stalks are thick or thin from the moment they sprout from the ground.  &lt;ref name=&quot;UIllinoisExtension&quot; /&gt;

Green asparagus is eaten worldwide, though the availability of imports throughout the year has made it less of a delicacy than it once was.&lt;ref name=blamey&gt;Blamey, M. &amp; Grey-Wilson, C. (1989). ''Flora of Britain and Northern Europe''. {{ISBN|0-340-40170-2}}.&lt;/ref&gt; In Europe, however, the &quot;asparagus season is a highlight of the [[foodie]] calendar&quot;; in the UK this traditionally begins on 23 April and ends on [[Midsummer]] Day.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.oxfordtimes.co.uk/leisure/4329516.Time_to_glory_in_asparagus_again/ ''Oxford Times'': &quot;Time to glory in asparagus again&quot;.] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090907192444/http://www.oxfordtimes.co.uk/leisure/4329516.Time_to_glory_in_asparagus_again/ |date=7 September 2009 }}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.british-asparagus.co.uk/|title=Page Redirection}}&lt;/ref&gt; As in continental Europe, due to the short growing season and demand for local produce, asparagus commands a premium price.

=== White asparagus ===
[[File:Steam-boiling_green_asparagus.jpg|thumb|Steam boiling asparagus in a pot]]
White asparagus is very popular in Europe and western Asia.{{Citation needed|date=September 2017}} White asparagus is the result of applying a [[Blanching (horticulture)|blanching]] technique while the asparagus shoots are growing. To cultivate white asparagus, the shoots are covered with soil as they grow, i.e. [[Hilling|earthed up]]; without exposure to sunlight, no [[photosynthesis]] starts, and the shoots remain white. Compared to green asparagus, the locally cultivated so-called &quot;white gold&quot; or &quot;edible ivory&quot; asparagus, also referred to as &quot;the royal vegetable&quot;,&lt;ref name=&quot;witgoud_12&quot;&gt;{{cite web|url=http://eten-en-drinken.infoyo.nl/producten/14450-wit-goud-en-koningin-der-groente-vorstelijke-asperges.html|title=Wit goud en koningin der groente: vorstelijke asperges|date=20 May 2009|publisher=Infoyo (web publisher)|location=Netherlands|language=Dutch|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120119040848/http://eten-en-drinken.infoyo.nl/producten/14450-wit-goud-en-koningin-der-groente-vorstelijke-asperges.html|archive-date=19 January 2012|accessdate=26 August 2011}}&lt;/ref&gt; is believed to be  less bitter and much more tender. Freshness is very important, and the lower ends of white asparagus must be peeled before cooking or raw consumption.

Only seasonally on the menu, asparagus dishes are advertised outside many restaurants, usually from late April to June. For the French style, asparagus is often boiled or steamed and served with [[Hollandaise sauce]], [[White sauce]], melted butter or most recently with olive oil and [[Parmesan cheese]].&lt;ref name=&quot;French&quot;&gt;{{cite book|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KurMDAAAQBAJ&amp;q=asperge%20livre%20cuisine&amp;pg=PT354|chapter=“Chapitre XVI Légumes 71.Légumes” |author1=Jules Gouffé |author2=Etienne Antoine |author3=Eugène Ronjat|title=Le Livre de cuisine: Comprenant la cuisine de ménage et la grande cuisine, 1893.|date=5 August 2016 |isbn=9782346013760 |language=French|accessdate=28 April 2020}} (''Asperge'' is French for asparagus.)&lt;/ref&gt; Tall, narrow asparagus cooking pots allow the shoots to be steamed gently, their tips staying out of the water.

During the German ''Spargelsaison'' or ''Spargelzeit'' (&quot;asparagus season&quot; or &quot;asparagus time&quot;), the asparagus season that traditionally finishes on 24 June, roadside stands and open-air markets sell about half of the country's white asparagus consumption.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|last=Evans|first=Stephen|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-17753372|title=Asparagus, royalty and the joys of seasonal eating|date=21 April 2012|work=BBC News|accessdate=22 April 2012}}&lt;/ref&gt;

In India, especially in Maharashtra state, it is not usually cultivated, but grows naturally in the farms during monsoon. Farmers from rural area and some tribal people use the young asparagus plants as a vegetable in their meals.{{Citation needed|reason=this fact or claim is interesting but needs a reference; is it really mainly in Maharashtra and not the whole of India?|date=August 2020}}

&lt;br /&gt;

== Cultivation ==
{{See also|List of asparagus diseases}}

Since asparagus often originates in maritime habitats, it thrives in soils that are too saline for normal weeds to grow. Thus, a little salt was traditionally used to suppress weeds in beds intended for asparagus; this has the disadvantage that the soil cannot be used for anything else. Some places are better for growing asparagus than others. The fertility of the soil is a large factor. &quot;Crowns&quot; are planted in winter, and the first shoots appear in spring; the first pickings or &quot;thinnings&quot; are known as sprue asparagus. Sprue has thin stems.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web
 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/food/glossary/s.shtml?sprue_asparagus
 |title=Glossary – 'S'
 |publisher=[[BBC Food]]
 |accessdate=8 June 2007
 }}&lt;/ref&gt;

A breed of &quot;early season asparagus&quot; that can be harvested two months earlier than usual was announced by a UK grower in early 2011.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/foodanddrink/8392483/New-breed-of-early-asparagus-hits-the-shelves.html|title=New breed of early asparagus hits the shelves|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|date=19 March 2011|accessdate=20 March 2011}}&lt;/ref&gt; This variety does not need to lie dormant and blooms at {{convert|7|C|F}}, rather than the usual {{convert|9|C|F}}.

&lt;!-- Already given above: The [[blanching (horticulture)|blanching]] of white asparagus is obtained by the labour-intensive [[hilling]] cultivation method, to distinguish its gastronomical qualities from those of the green plant, which is the same botanical variety. --&gt;
Purple asparagus differs from its green and white counterparts in having high sugar and low fibre levels. Purple asparagus was originally developed in Italy, near the city of [[Albenga]] and commercialized under the variety name 'Violetto d' Albenga'.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|last1=Raymond|first1=Francine|title=Asparagus: this season's hottest shades to grow|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/gardening/howtogrow/10842082/Asparagus-this-seasons-hottest-shades-to-grow.html|accessdate=21 May 2017|work=The Telegraph|date=21 May 2014}}&lt;/ref&gt; 

