=== Companion planting ===
Asparagus is said to be a useful [[companion plant]] for [[tomato]]es, as the tomato plant repels the [[asparagus beetle]]. Asparagus may repel some harmful root nematodes that affect tomato plants.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.pfaf.org/user/Plant.aspx?LatinName=Asparagus+officinalis|title=Plants for a Future}}&lt;/ref&gt;

== Commercial production ==
[[File:2005asparagus.PNG|thumb|right|400px|Cultivated asparagus output in 2005 shown as a percentage of the top producer (China)&lt;br /&gt; {{legend|green|100}} {{legend|yellow|10}} {{legend|red|1}}]]

The top asparagus importers (2016) were the United States (214,735 tonnes), followed by [[Germany]] (24,484 tonnes), and Canada (19,224 tonnes).&lt;ref name=faostat&gt;{{cite web |url=http://www.fao.org/faostat/en/#rankings/countries_by_commodity |title = Food and Agriculture Organisation Statistics (FAOSTAT) |accessdate=8 September 2019}}&lt;/ref&gt;

China is by far the world's largest producer: in 2017 it produced 7,845,162 tonnes, followed by [[Peru]] with 383,098 tonnes and [[Mexico]] with 245,681 tonnes.&lt;ref name=faostat /&gt; U.S. production was concentrated in [[California]], [[Michigan]], and [[Washington (state)|Washington]].&lt;ref name=faostat336&gt;{{cite web
 |url=http://faostat.fao.org/site/336/DesktopDefault.aspx?PageID=336
 |title=Food and Agriculture Organisation Statistics (FAOSTAT)
 |accessdate=11 November 2007
 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071107164115/http://faostat.fao.org/site/336/DesktopDefault.aspx?PageID=336
 |archivedate=7 November 2007
 |url-status=live
 
}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref name=nass&gt;{{cite book
 |author=USDA
 |title=Vegetables 2005 Summary
 |date=January 2006
 |publisher=National Agricultural Statistics Service
 }}&lt;/ref&gt;
The annual production for white asparagus in Germany is 57,000 tonnes (61% of consumer demand).&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web
 |url         = http://www.germanfoods.org/consumer/documents/WhiteAsparagusPressRelease.doc
 |format      = DOC
 |publisher   = German Agricultural Marketing Board
 |title       = Asparagus: The King of Vegetables
 |author      = Spence, Molly
 |accessdate  = 26 February 2007
 |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20071013032017/http://www.germanfoods.org/consumer/documents/WhiteAsparagusPressRelease.doc
 |archivedate = 13 October 2007
 |url-status     = dead
 |df          = dmy
}}&lt;/ref&gt;

When grown under [[polytunnel|tunnels]], growers can extend the harvest season. In the UK, it is estimated that the asparagus harvest season can begin as early as mid-February and continue into late autumn by growing cold-resistant cultivars under heated polytunnels. Furthermore, late season harvests can be achieved using 'reverse season growth' where spears are left to fern between March–August and harvested in September–October.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news |last1=Hart |first1=Carolyn |title=Asparagus in autumn? Meet the man behind its extended season |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/foodanddrink/recipes/11838908/Asparagus-in-autumn-Meet-the-man-behind-its-extended-season.html |accessdate=3 January 2019 |date=5 September 2015}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://vegetablegrowersnews.com/article/u-k-grower-creates-asparagus-market/|title=U.K. grower creates asparagus market – Vegetable Growers News|work=Vegetable Growers News}}&lt;/ref&gt;
